# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: azure-app-service
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:azure-app-service/application-server] An **application server** is a server that hosts applications or software that delivers a business application through a communication protocol.
[src:azure-app-service/application-server] For a typical web application, the application server sits behind the web servers.
[src:azure-app-service/application-server] An application server framework is a service layer model.
[src:azure-app-service/application-server] It includes software components available to a software developer through an application programming interface.
[src:azure-app-service/application-server] An application server may have features such as clustering, fail-over, and load-balancing.
[src:azure-app-service/application-server] The goal is for developers to focus on the business logic.
[src:azure-app-service/application-server] Jakarta EE (formerly Java EE or J2EE) defines the core set of API and features of Java application servers.
[src:azure-app-service/application-server] The Jakarta EE infrastructure is partitioned into logical containers.
[src:azure-app-service/application-server] Microsoft's .NET positions their middle-tier applications and services infrastructure in the Windows Server operating system and the .NET Framework technologies in the role of an application server.
[src:azure-app-service/application-server] PHP application servers run and manage PHP applications.
[src:azure-app-service/application-server] Mobile application servers provide data delivery to mobile devices.
[src:azure-app-service/autoscaling] Autoscaling differs from having a fixed daily, weekly, or yearly cycle of server use in that it is responsive to actual usage patterns, and thus reduces the potential downside of having too few or too many servers for the traffic load.
[src:azure-app-service/autoscaling] For instance, if traffic is usually lower at midnight, then a static scaling solution might schedule some servers to sleep at night, but this might result in downtime on a night where people happen to use the Internet more (for instance, due to a viral news event).
[src:azure-app-service/autoscaling] Autoscaling, on the other hand, can handle unexpected traffic spikes better.
[src:azure-app-service/autoscaling] In the list below, we use the terminology used by Amazon Web Services (AWS).
[src:azure-app-service/autoscaling] However, alternative names are noted and terminology that is specific to the names of Amazon services is not used for the names.
[src:azure-app-service/autoscaling] Amazon Web Services launched the Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2) service in August 2006, that allowed developers to programmatically create and terminate instances (machines).
[src:azure-app-service/autoscaling] At the time of initial launch, AWS did not offer autoscaling, but the ability to programmatically create and terminate instances gave developers the flexibility to write their own code for autoscaling.
[src:azure-app-service/autoscaling] Third-party autoscaling software for AWS began appearing around April 2008.
[src:azure-app-service/autoscaling] These included tools by Scalr and RightScale.
[src:azure-app-service/autoscaling] RightScale was used by Animoto, which was able to handle Facebook traffic by adopting autoscaling.
[src:azure-app-service/autoscaling] On May 18, 2009, Amazon launched its own autoscaling feature along with Elastic Load Balancing, as part of Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud.
[src:azure-app-service/autoscaling] Autoscaling is now an integral component of Amazon's EC2 offering.
[src:azure-app-service/autoscaling] Autoscaling on Amazon Web Services is done through a web browser or the command line tool.
[src:azure-app-service/autoscaling] In May 2016 Autoscaling was also offered in AWS ECS Service.
[src:azure-app-service/autoscaling] On-demand video provider Netflix documented their use of autoscaling with Amazon Web Services to meet their highly variable consumer needs.
[src:azure-app-service/autoscaling] They found that aggressive scaling up and delayed and cautious scaling down served their goals of uptime and responsiveness best.
[src:azure-app-service/autoscaling] In an article for *TechCrunch*, Zev Laderman, the co-founder and CEO of Newvem, a service that helps optimize AWS cloud infrastructure, recommended that startups use autoscaling in order to keep their Amazon Web Services costs low.
[src:azure-app-service/autoscaling] Various best practice guides for AWS use suggest using its autoscaling feature even in cases where the load is not variable.
[src:azure-app-service/autoscaling] Netflix's internal best practices require every instance to be in an autoscaling group, and its conformity monkey terminates any instance not in an autoscaling group in order to enforce this best practice.
[src:azure-app-service/autoscaling] On June 27, 2013, Microsoft announced that it was adding autoscaling support to its Windows Azure cloud computing platform.
[src:azure-app-service/autoscaling] Documentation for the feature is available on the Microsoft Developer Network.
[src:azure-app-service/autoscaling] Oracle Cloud Platform allows server instances to automatically scale a cluster in or out by defining an auto-scaling rule.
[src:azure-app-service/autoscaling] These rules are based on CPU and/or memory utilization and determine when to add or remove nodes.
[src:azure-app-service/autoscaling] On November 17, 2014, the Google Compute Engine announced a public beta of its autoscaling feature for use in Google Cloud Platform applications.
[src:azure-app-service/autoscaling] As of March 2015, the autoscaling tool is still in Beta.
[src:azure-app-service/autoscaling] In a blog post in August 2014, a Facebook engineer disclosed that the company had started using autoscaling to bring down its energy costs.
[src:azure-app-service/autoscaling] The blog post reported a 27% decline in energy use for low traffic hours (around midnight) and a 10-15% decline in energy use over the typical 24-hour cycle.
[src:azure-app-service/autoscaling] Autoscaling by default uses *reactive* decision approach for dealing with traffic scaling: scaling only happens in response to real-time changes in metrics.
[src:azure-app-service/autoscaling] In some cases, particularly when the changes occur very quickly, this reactive approach to scaling is insufficient.
[src:azure-app-service/autoscaling] Two other kinds of autoscaling decision approaches are described below.
[src:azure-app-service/autoscaling] This is an approach to autoscaling where changes are made to the minimum size, maximum size, or desired capacity of the autoscaling group at specific times of day.
[src:azure-app-service/autoscaling] Scheduled scaling is useful, for instance, if there is a known traffic load increase or decrease at specific times of the day, but the change is too sudden for reactive approach based autoscaling to respond fast enough.
[src:azure-app-service/autoscaling] AWS autoscaling groups support scheduled scaling.
[src:azure-app-service/autoscaling] This approach to autoscaling uses predictive analytics.
[src:azure-app-service/autoscaling] The idea is to combine recent usage trends with historical usage data as well as other kinds of data to predict usage in the future, and autoscale based on these predictions.
[src:azure-app-service/autoscaling] For parts of their infrastructure and specific workloads, Netflix found that Scryer, their predictive analytics engine, gave better results than Amazon's reactive autoscaling approach.
[src:azure-app-service/autoscaling] On November 20, 2018, AWS announced that predictive scaling would be available as part of its autoscaling offering.
[src:azure-app-service/continuous-deployment] Continuous deployment contrasts with *continuous delivery* (also abbreviated CD), a similar approach in which software functionalities are also frequently delivered and deemed to be potentially capable of being deployed, but are actually not deployed.
[src:azure-app-service/continuous-deployment] As such, continuous deployment can be viewed as a more complete form of automation than continuous delivery.
[src:azure-app-service/continuous-deployment] Continuous deployment has been adopted by software companies such as Meta, Microsoft, Atlassian, IBM, Adobe, and Tesla.
[src:azure-app-service/continuous-deployment] Continuous deployment extends the principles of continuous integration and delivery by including fully automated production deployment without the need for manual approval, instead relying on rigorous automated testing.
[src:azure-app-service/continuous-deployment] Reviews may still take place in the form developer-developer code reviews, but the need for intermediary reviewers such as a change-advisory board is minimized.
[src:azure-app-service/continuous-deployment] Because code changes are deployed automatically, continuous deployment requires a much higher standard of automated testing, as test quality determines the reliability of releases.
[src:azure-app-service/continuous-deployment] Without this, the risk of introducing production failures outweighs the benefits of deployment automation.
[src:azure-app-service/continuous-deployment] In addition, continuous deployment emphasizes small incremental changes and dark launches through the use of feature toggles.
[src:azure-app-service/continuous-deployment] Developers can deploy code into production months before a public release by gradually adding functionality in small chunks, verifying stability, and then enabling the feature for users when it is considered ready.
[src:azure-app-service/continuous-deployment] Continuous deployment removes the need to wait for releases, as once a change passes internal testing it is automatically deployed to production.
[src:azure-app-service/continuous-deployment] This allows for shorter time-to-market and more frequent releases, which in turn increases customer satisfaction and provides companies with more marketing opportunities.
[src:azure-app-service/continuous-deployment] A major motivation for continuous deployment is that deploying software into the field more often makes it easier to find, catch, and fix bugs.
[src:azure-app-service/continuous-deployment] Deploying small, incremental changes makes it easier to trace the origin of bugs, since issues will be isolated to a recent and relatively small code change.
[src:azure-app-service/continuous-deployment] Under this methodology, new software features can be released to customers more quickly and frequently after their development, accelerating the delivery of value to customers and enhancing customer satisfaction.
[src:azure-app-service/continuous-deployment] Teams can begin to collect customer feedback almost immediately, driving rapid innovation of relevant features.
[src:azure-app-service/continuous-deployment] Continuous delivery requires a significant investment in adequate test coverage, real-time monitoring, and strong continuous integration pipelines to prevent bugs from reaching production.
[src:azure-app-service/continuous-deployment] Customers may also find software that is constantly changing creates a learning curve which can negatively affect their experience.
[src:azure-app-service/continuous-deployment] Moving to continuous delivery is also a culture shift for developers who are accustomed to traditional release cycles, often requiring a proven DevOps process.
[src:azure-app-service/continuous-deployment] Adopting this process requires collaboration among multiple stakeholders, including development teams, leadership, operations, and quality assurance.
[src:azure-app-service/continuous-deployment] In an environment in which data-centric microservices provide the functionality, and where the microservices can have multiple instances, continuous deployment consists of instantiating the new version of a microservice and retiring the old version once it has drained all the requests in flight.
[src:azure-app-service/platform-as-a-service] The first public platform as a service was Zimki, launched by Fotango, a London-based company owned by Canon Europe.
[src:azure-app-service/platform-as-a-service] It was developed in 2005, had a beta launch in March 2006 and a public launch at EuroOSCON in 2006.
[src:azure-app-service/platform-as-a-service] At the time of its closure, Zimki had several thousand developer accounts.
[src:azure-app-service/platform-as-a-service] It had demonstrated the technical viability of Platform as a Service, but also provided the first example of the perils of being dependent on a single provider.
[src:azure-app-service/platform-as-a-service] The original intent of PaaS was to simplify the writing of code, with the infrastructure and operations handled by the PaaS provider.
[src:azure-app-service/platform-as-a-service] Originally, all PaaSes were in the public cloud.
[src:azure-app-service/platform-as-a-service] Because many companies did not want to have everything in the public cloud, private and hybrid PaaS options (managed by internal IT departments) were created.
[src:azure-app-service/platform-as-a-service] PaaS provides an environment for developers and companies to create, host and deploy applications, saving developers from the complexities of infrastructure (setting up, configuring and managing elements such as servers and databases).
[src:azure-app-service/platform-as-a-service] PaaS can improve the speed of developing an app, and allow its user to focus on the application itself.
[src:azure-app-service/platform-as-a-service] With PaaS, the customer manages applications and data, while the provider (in public PaaS) or IT department (in private PaaS) manages runtime, middleware, operating system, virtualization, servers, storage and networking.
[src:azure-app-service/platform-as-a-service] Development tools provided by the vendor are customized according to the needs of the user.
[src:azure-app-service/platform-as-a-service] The user can choose to maintain the software, or have the vendor maintain it.
[src:azure-app-service/platform-as-a-service] Besides the service engineering aspects, PaaS offerings include mechanisms for service management, such as monitoring, workflow management, discovery and reservation.
[src:azure-app-service/platform-as-a-service] Disadvantages of various PaaS providers as cited by their users include increased pricing at larger scales, lack of operational features, reduced control, and the difficulties of traffic routing systems.
[src:azure-app-service/platform-as-a-service] There are several types of PaaS, including public, private and hybrid.
[src:azure-app-service/platform-as-a-service] PaaS was originally intended for applications on public cloud services, before expanding to include private and hybrid options.
[src:azure-app-service/platform-as-a-service] Public PaaS is derived from software as a service (SaaS), and is situated in cloud computing between SaaS and infrastructure as a service (IaaS).
[src:azure-app-service/platform-as-a-service] SaaS is software hosted in the cloud so that it does not reside or run on customer computers.
[src:azure-app-service/platform-as-a-service] IaaS provides virtual hardware from a provider with adjustable scalability.
[src:azure-app-service/platform-as-a-service] In IaaS, the server is managed by the user, whereas in PaaS by the provider.
[src:azure-app-service/platform-as-a-service] A private PaaS can typically be downloaded and installed either in a company's on-premises data center, or in a public cloud.
[src:azure-app-service/platform-as-a-service] Once the software is installed on one or more machines, the private PaaS arranges the application and database components into a single hosting platform.
[src:azure-app-service/platform-as-a-service] Hybrid PaaS is typically a deployment consisting of a mix of public and private deployments.
[src:azure-app-service/platform-as-a-service] A communications platform as a service (CPaaS) is a cloud-based platform that enables developers to add real-time communications features (voice, video, and messaging) in their own applications without building back-end infrastructure and interfaces.
[src:azure-app-service/platform-as-a-service] Also, CPaaS and hardware and software specifications are specifically designed to support (tele)communications applications.
[src:azure-app-service/platform-as-a-service] These applications and their usage are much more sensitive to jitter, latency and packet losses.
[src:azure-app-service/platform-as-a-service] Hosted PBX, cellular networks, (near real-time) applications typically are deployed on CPaaS platforms.
[src:azure-app-service/platform-as-a-service] Initiated in 2012, mobile PaaS (mPaaS) provides development capabilities for mobile app designers and developers.
[src:azure-app-service/platform-as-a-service] The Yankee Group identified mPaaS as one of its themes for 2014.
[src:azure-app-service/platform-as-a-service] There are various types of PaaS providers.
[src:azure-app-service/platform-as-a-service] All offer application hosting and a deployment environment, along with various integrated services.
[src:azure-app-service/platform-as-a-service] Services offer varying levels of scalability and maintenance.
[src:azure-app-service/platform-as-a-service] Developers can write an application and upload it to a PaaS that supports their software language of choice, and the application runs on that PaaS.
[src:azure-app-service/platform-as-a-service] The UK Government encourages departments to make use of public cloud solutions as a first option.
[src:azure-app-service/platform-as-a-service] PaaS is in use within UK Government but the technology community within government notes that PaaS providers may restrict the software, languages and interfaces they are willing to support.
[src:azure-app-service/platform-as-a-service] The Government operated its own GOV.UK PaaS service from 2015 until 2023, but this has now been decommissioned.
[src:azure-app-service/web-application] A **web application** (or **web app**) is application software that is created with web technologies and runs via a web browser.
[src:azure-app-service/web-application] Web applications emerged during the late 1990s and allowed for the server to dynamically build a response to the request, in contrast to static web pages.
[src:azure-app-service/web-application] Web applications are commonly distributed via a web server.
[src:azure-app-service/web-application] There are several different tier systems that web applications use to communicate between the web browsers, the client interface, and server data.
[src:azure-app-service/web-application] Each system has its own uses as they function in different ways.
[src:azure-app-service/web-application] However, there are many security risks that developers must be aware of during development; proper measures to protect user data are vital.
[src:azure-app-service/web-application] Web applications are often constructed with the use of a web application framework.
[src:azure-app-service/web-application] Single-page applications (SPAs) and progressive web apps (PWAs) are two architectural approaches to creating web applications that provide a user experience similar to native apps, including features such as smooth navigation, offline support, and faster interactions.
[src:azure-app-service/web-application] Modern browsers such as Chrome offer sandboxing for every browser tab which improves security and restricts access to local resources.
[src:azure-app-service/web-application] No software installation is required as the app runs within the browser which reduces the need for managing software installations.
[src:azure-app-service/web-application] With the use of remote cloud services, customers do not need to manage servers as that can be left to the developer and the cloud service and can use the software with a relatively low power, low-resource PC such as a thin client.
[src:azure-app-service/web-application] The source code of the application can stay the same across operating systems and devices of users with the use of responsive web design, since it only needs to be compatible with web browsers which adhere to web standards, making the code highly portable and saving on development time.
[src:azure-app-service/web-application] Numerous JavaScript frameworks and CSS frameworks facilitate development.
[src:azure-app-service/web-application] The concept of a "web application" was first introduced in the Java language in the Servlet Specification version 2.2, which was released in 1999.
[src:azure-app-service/web-application] At that time, both JavaScript and XML had already been developed, but the XMLHttpRequest object had only been recently introduced on Internet Explorer 5 as an ActiveX object.
[src:azure-app-service/web-application] Beginning around the early 2000s, applications such as "Myspace (2003), Gmail (2004), Digg (2004), [and] Google Maps (2005)," started to make their client sides more and more interactive.
[src:azure-app-service/web-application] A web page script is able to contact the server for storing/retrieving data without downloading an entire web page.
[src:azure-app-service/web-application] The practice became known as Ajax in 2005.
[src:azure-app-service/web-application] Eventually this was replaced by web APIs using JSON, accessed via JavaScript asynchronously on the client side.
[src:azure-app-service/web-application] In earlier computing models like client-server, the processing load for the application was shared between code on the server and code installed on each client locally.
[src:azure-app-service/web-application] In other words, an application had its own pre-compiled client program which served as its user interface and had to be separately installed on each user's personal computer.
[src:azure-app-service/web-application] An upgrade to the server-side code of the application would typically also require an upgrade to the client-side code installed on each user workstation, adding to the support cost and decreasing productivity.
[src:azure-app-service/web-application] Additionally, both the client and server components of the application were bound tightly to a particular computer architecture and operating system, which made porting them to other systems prohibitively expensive for all but the largest applications.
[src:azure-app-service/web-application] Later, in 1995, Netscape introduced the client-side scripting language called JavaScript, which allowed programmers to add dynamic elements to the user interface that ran on the client side.
[src:azure-app-service/web-application] Essentially, instead of sending data to the server in order to generate an entire web page, the embedded scripts of the downloaded page can perform various tasks such as input validation or showing/hiding parts of the page.
[src:azure-app-service/web-application] Traditional PC applications are typically single-tiered, residing solely on the client machine.
[src:azure-app-service/web-application] In contrast, web applications inherently facilitate a multi-tiered architecture.
[src:azure-app-service/web-application] Though many variations are possible, the most common structure is the three-tiered application.
[src:azure-app-service/web-application] In its most common form, the three tiers are called *presentation*, *application* and *storage*.
[src:azure-app-service/web-application] The first tier, presentation, refers to a web browser itself.
[src:azure-app-service/web-application] The second tier refers to any engine using dynamic web content technology (such as ASP, CGI, ColdFusion, Dart, JSP/Java, Node.js, PHP, Python or Ruby on Rails).
[src:azure-app-service/web-application] The third tier refers to a database that stores data and determines the structure of a user interface.
[src:azure-app-service/web-application] Essentially, when using the three-tiered system, the web browser sends requests to the engine, which then services them by making queries and updates against the database and generates a user interface.
[src:azure-app-service/web-application] The 3-tier solution may fall short when dealing with more complex applications, and may need to be replaced with the n-tiered approach; the greatest benefit of which is how business logic (which resides on the application tier) is broken down into a more fine-grained model.
[src:azure-app-service/web-application] Another benefit would be to add an integration tier, which separates the data tier and provides an easy-to-use interface to access the data.
[src:azure-app-service/web-application] For example, the client data would be accessed by calling a "list_clients()" function instead of making an SQL query directly against the client table on the database.
[src:azure-app-service/web-application] This allows the underlying database to be replaced without making any change to the other tiers.
[src:azure-app-service/web-application] There are some who view a web application as a two-tier architecture.
[src:azure-app-service/web-application] This can be a "smart" client that performs all the work and queries a "dumb" server, or a "dumb" client that relies on a "smart" server.
[src:azure-app-service/web-application] The client would handle the presentation tier, the server would have the database (storage tier), and the business logic (application tier) would be on one of them or on both.
[src:azure-app-service/web-application] While this increases the scalability of the applications and separates the display and the database, it still does not allow for true specialization of layers, so most applications will outgrow this model.
[src:azure-app-service/web-application] Security breaches on these kinds of applications are a major concern because it can involve both enterprise information and private customer data.
[src:azure-app-service/web-application] Protecting these assets is an important part of any web application, and there are some key operational areas that must be included in the development process.
[src:azure-app-service/web-application] This includes processes for authentication, authorization, asset handling, input, and logging and auditing.
[src:azure-app-service/web-application] Building security into the applications from the beginning is sometimes more effective and less disruptive in the long run.
[src:azure-app-service/web-application] Writing web applications is simplified with the use of web application frameworks.
[src:azure-app-service/web-application] These frameworks facilitate rapid application development by allowing a development team to focus on the parts of their application which are unique to their goals without having to resolve common development issues such as user management.
[src:azure-app-service/web-application] In addition, there is potential for the development of applications on Internet operating systems, although currently there are not many viable platforms that fit this model.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] A **web hosting service** is a type of Internet hosting service that hosts websites for clients, i.e. it offers the facilities required for them to create and maintain a site and makes it accessible on the World Wide Web.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] Companies providing web hosting services are sometimes called *web hosts*.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] Until 1991, the Internet was restricted to use only "... for research and education in the sciences and engineering ..." and was used for email, telnet, FTP and USENET traffic—but only a tiny number of web pages.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] The World Wide Web protocols had only just been written, and there wouldn't be a graphical web browser for Mac or Windows computers until the end of 1993.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] Even after there was some opening up of Internet access, the situation was confused until 1995.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] To host a website on the internet, an individual or company would need their own computer or server.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] As not all companies had the budget or expertise to do this, web hosting services began to offer to host users' websites on their own servers, without the client needing to own the necessary infrastructure required to operate the website.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] The owners of the websites, also called webmasters, would be able to create a website that would be hosted on the web hosting service's server and published to the web by the web hosting service.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] As the number of users on the World Wide Web grew, the pressure for companies, both large and small, to have an online presence grew.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] By 1995, companies such as GeoCities, Angelfire and Tripod were offering free hosting.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] Static web page files can be uploaded via File Transfer Protocol (FTP) or a web interface, or automatically deployed from a repository using a Continuous Integration tool.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] For example, static page hosting services such as GitHub Pages or Cloudflare Pages often build directly from source control systems such as Git.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] The files are usually delivered to the Web "as is", or with minimal processing, e.g. by using a static site generator such as 11ty.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] Many Internet service providers (ISPs) offer this service free to subscribers.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] Individuals and organizations may also obtain web page hosting from alternative service providers.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] Free web hosting service is offered by different companies with limited services, sometimes supported by advertisements, and often limited when compared to paid hosting.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] Single page hosting is generally sufficient for personal web pages.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] Personal website hosting is typically free, advertisement-sponsored, or inexpensive.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] Business website hosting often has a higher expense depending upon the size and type of the site.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] Peer-to-peer web hosting is using peer-to-peer networking to distribute access to webpages.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] This is differentiated from the client–server model which involves the distribution of web data between dedicated web servers and user-end client computers.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] Peer-to-peer web hosting may also take the form of P2P web caches and content delivery networks.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] A complex site calls for a more comprehensive package that provides database support and application development platforms (e.g.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] ASP.NET, ColdFusion, Java EE, Perl/Plack, PHP or Ruby on Rails).
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] These facilities allow customers to write or install scripts for applications like forums and content management.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] Web hosting packages often include a web content management system, so the end-user does not have to worry about the more technical aspects.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] Secure Sockets Layer (SSL) is used for websites that wish to encrypt the transmitted data.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] Internet hosting services can run web servers.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] The scope of web hosting services varies greatly.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] One's website is placed on the same server as many other sites, ranging from a few sites to hundreds of websites.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] The features available with this type of service can be quite basic and not flexible in terms of software and updates.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] often sell shared web hosting and web companies often have reseller accounts to provide hosting for clients.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] Allows clients to become web hosts themselves.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] Resellers could function, for individual domains, under any combination of these listed types of hosting, depending on who they are affiliated with as a reseller.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] Resellers' accounts may vary tremendously in size: they may have their own virtual dedicated server to a colocated server.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] Many resellers provide a nearly identical service to their provider's shared hosting plan and provide the technical support themselves.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] (VPS), divides server resources into virtual servers, where resources can be allocated in a way that does not directly reflect the underlying hardware.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] VPS will often be allocated resources based on a one server to many VPSs relationship, however virtualisation may be done for a number of reasons, including the ability to move a VPS container between servers.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] Customers are sometimes responsible for patching and maintaining the server (unmanaged server) or the VPS provider may provide server admin tasks for the customer (managed server).
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] for Linux/administrator access for Windows); however, the user typically does not own the server.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] One type of dedicated hosting is self-managed or unmanaged.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] This is usually the least expensive for dedicated plans.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] The user has full administrative access to the server, which means the client is responsible for the security and maintenance of their own dedicated server.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] The user gets their own web server but is not allowed full control over it (user is denied root access for Linux/administrator access for Windows); however, they are allowed to manage their data via FTP or other remote management tools.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] The user is disallowed full control so that the provider can guarantee quality of service by not allowing the user to modify the server or potentially create configuration problems.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] The user typically does not own the server.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] Similar to the dedicated web hosting service, but the user owns the colo server; the hosting company provides physical space that the server takes up and takes care of the server.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] This is the most powerful and expensive type of web hosting service.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] In most cases, the colocation provider may provide little to no support directly for their client's machine, providing only the electrical, Internet access, and storage facilities for the server.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] In most cases for colo, the client would have their own administrator visit the data center on site to do any hardware upgrades or changes.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] enclosures and standard system configurations.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] Hosting based on clustered load-balanced servers.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] A cloud hosted website may be more reliable than alternatives since other computers in the cloud can compensate when a single piece of hardware goes down.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] Also, local power disruptions or even natural disasters are less problematic for cloud hosted sites, as cloud hosting is decentralized.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] Cloud hosting also allows providers to charge users only for resources consumed by the user, rather than a flat fee for the amount the user expects they will use, or a fixed cost upfront hardware investment.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] Cloud hosting users can request additional resources on-demand such as only during periods of peak traffic, while offloading IT management to the cloud hosting service.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] Having multiple servers hosting the same content for better resource utilization.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] Clustered servers are a perfect solution for high-availability dedicated hosting, or creating a scalable web hosting solution.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] A cluster may separate web serving from database hosting capability.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] (Usually web hosts use clustered hosting for their shared hosting plans, as there are multiple benefits to the mass managing of clients).
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] This form of distributed hosting is when a server cluster acts like a grid and is composed of multiple nodes.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] These can be purpose-built machines or more commonly old PCs.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] The host may also provide an interface or control panel for managing the web server and installing scripts, as well as other modules and service applications like e-mail.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] A web server that does not use a control panel for managing the hosting account, is often referred to as a "headless" server.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] Some hosts specialize in certain software or services (e.g. e-commerce, blogs, etc.).
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] The availability of a website is measured by the percentage of a year in which the website is publicly accessible and reachable via the Internet.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] This is different from measuring the uptime of a system.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] Uptime refers to the system itself being online.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] Uptime does not take into account being able to reach it as in the event of a network outage.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] A hosting provider's Service Level Agreement (SLA) may include a certain amount of scheduled downtime per year in order to perform maintenance on the systems.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] This scheduled downtime is often excluded from the SLA timeframe, and needs to be subtracted from the Total Time when availability is calculated.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] Depending on the wording of an SLA, if the availability of a system drops below that in the signed SLA, a hosting provider often will provide a partial refund for time lost.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] How downtime is determined changes from provider to provider, therefore reading the SLA is imperative.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] Not all providers release uptime statistics.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] Because web hosting services host websites belonging to their customers, online security is an important concern.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] When a customer agrees to use a web hosting service, they are relinquishing control of the security of their site to the company that is hosting the site.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] The level of security that a web hosting service offers is extremely important to a prospective customer and can be a major factor when considering which provider a customer may choose.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] Web hosting servers can be attacked by malicious users in different ways, including uploading malware or malicious code onto a hosted website.
[src:azure-app-service/web-hosting-service] These attacks may be done for different reasons, including stealing credit card data, launching a Distributed Denial of Service Attack (DDoS) or spamming.
